    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.8\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 12.5.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm latest nightly\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nwezterm\n\n### Installation\n\nrelease\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nRun the following command\r\n\r\n```\r\nTERM=wezterm nvim --clean -c \"set title titlestring=hello\"\r\n```\r\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe terminal title should be changed to `hello`\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nit is not, it just shows the full command: `TERM=wezterm nvim --clean -c \"set title titlestring=hello\"`.\r\n\r\nBase on discussion on https://github.com/wez/wezterm/issues/2112, it seems that it is due to nvim matching `xterm` to decide terminal ability instead of using terminfo file.\r\n\r\nThere is workaround (change wezterm terminfo file), but it is not elegant.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "\r\n> There is workaround (change wezterm terminfo file), but it is not elegant.\r\n\r\nDoesn't that mean wezterm's terminfo is wrong? This is precisely the reason Nvim has workarounds like:\r\n\r\n> nvim matching `xterm` to decide terminal ability instead of using terminfo file.\r\n\r\nHowever for titlestring, we could drastically relax our checks, and allow it for most terminals.",
